item.title: Neoliberalism – the ideology at the root of all our problems
item.excerpt: Imagine if the people of the Soviet Union had never heard of communism. The ideology that dominates our lives has, for most of us, no name. Mention it in conversation and you’ll be rewarded with a shrug. Even if your listeners have heard the term before, they will struggle to define it.

item.title: What to do with billions of useless humans?
item.excerpt: It is no news that machines have come to largely replace physical labor and computers surpass human beings in processing data. But in the future, the development of artificial intelligence may render humans obsolete even in the realm of emotional intelligence, according to Yuval Harari.

item.title: Soon We Won't Program Computers. We'll Train Them Like Dogs
item.excerpt: Before the invention of the computer, most experimental psychologists thought the brain was an unknowable black box. You could analyze a subject's behavior—ring bell, dog salivates—but thoughts, memories, emotions? That stuff was obscure and inscrutable, beyond the reach of science.

item.title: A controversial theory may explain the real reason humans have allergies
item.excerpt: For me, it was hornets. One summer afternoon when I was 12, I ran into an overgrown field near a friend’s house and kicked a hornet nest the size of a football. An angry squadron of insects clamped onto my leg; their stings felt like scorching needles.

item.title: Experiment and Scandal
item.excerpt: We are living in a time of great experiments. They are not happening in the lab. They are happening in the real world. And they are being financed by real people. We are witnessing the de-institutionalization of experimentation.

item.title: Agile no longer addresses the fundamental bottleneck
item.excerpt: I recently saw a question posed as to whether Agile is dead. Agile isn’t dead. However, Agile no longer addresses the main bottleneck to delivering value. The bottleneck has shifted. Let’s look at why that is the case and to where the bottleneck has shifted.

item.title: Anti-If: The missing patterns

item.excerpt: Secrecy is a virtual religion in Washington. Those who violate its dogma have been punished in the harshest and most excessive manner — at least when they possess little political power or influence.

item.excerpt: There are lots of stories about the formation of AWS, but this much we know: 10 years ago, Amazon Web Services, the cloud Infrastructure as a Service arm of Amazon.com, was launched with little fanfare as a side business for Amazon.com.

item.title: Is It Time For Federal Anti-Gentrification Zones In NYC?
item.excerpt: The federal government should establish neighborhood anti-gentrification zones where vulnerable tenants could form cooperatives to purchase their apartment buildings away from predatory landlords, according to a policy report revealed today by Democratic State Senator Adriano Espaillat.

item.title: Dallas deployment of robot bomb to kill suspect is “without precedent”
item.excerpt: Early Friday morning, after being attacked by gunmen who had already killed five police officers and injured several other officers along with two civilians in the wake of a protest, the Dallas Police Department deployed a bomb disposal robot. item.title: Google's Post-Quantum Cryptography
item.excerpt: News has been bubbling about an announcement by Google that it’s starting to experiment with public-key cryptography that’s resistant to cryptanalysis by a quantum computer. Specifically, it’s experimenting with the New Hope algorithm.

item.title: The Vast Left-Wing Media Conspiracy to Make Donald Trump Look Like a Bigot
item.excerpt: On Saturday, Donald Trump tweeted an image that had previously circulated among anti-Semites on social media. It was a six-pointed star, overlaid on a pile of money, with a picture of Hillary Clinton and the words “Most Corrupt Candidate Ever!” Predictably, the left erupted.
